## METHOD 2 — Upgrade: Mac Mini M4 + OBS + NDI

### What Changes

One dedicated machine — a Mac Mini M4 — runs OBS 24/7 and maintains a single unbroken RTMP stream to YouTube. It never stops. The lofi loop and the live stream are just **two scenes inside the same running OBS instance**. Switching between them is a Stream Deck button press. YouTube never sees a break.

```
Always-on stream:
[Mac Mini: OBS 24/7]
  Scene 1: HoldtLoop.mp4 (local media source)  ─────────┐
  Scene 2: NDI ← Windows Laptop OBS (when live) ─────────┤
                                                          ↓
                                               [Restream] → [YouTube @EIWerner]
                                                         ↘ [Twitch eiwerner]

Switch: Stream Deck button → instant scene change → zero blip
Laptop off? Scene 1 runs indefinitely. No SSH. No ritual. No blip.
```

### What NDI Is (Simply)

NDI is a protocol that lets one computer send its video and audio to another computer over your local network — the same network everything in your apartment is connected to. Your Windows laptop runs OBS, captures your camera and mic, and broadcasts that as an NDI signal. The Mac Mini receives it as a source inside its own OBS, exactly like a webcam.

**Requirements:**
- Both machines on the same local network
- Both connected via **wired ethernet** (gigabit) — WiFi cannot handle NDI's bandwidth (~100–150 Mbps)
- A gigabit switch or router with wired ports (your GL.iNet GL-MT6000 handles this)

**This only works at your home base.** At a café, your laptop and Mac Mini are on different networks — NDI doesn't work. For those sessions, you'd stream directly from your laptop as you do now.

### What This Unlocks

**Full OBS scene structure on the always-on machine.** Every scene you build — warmup, writing stream, gaming stream, cooldown, lofi radio — is available 24/7 via Stream Deck. The lofi loop is just one more OBS scene, not a separate system.

**Full Stream Deck + control.** Every button on your Stream Deck can control the Mac Mini's OBS via WebSocket over your local network. Scene switching, transitions, audio levels, everything — all from the Stream Deck whether your laptop is on or off.

**HTML browser sources work fully.** Your branded HTML overlays, countdown timers, the 28:07 warmup countdown — all run as browser sources inside Mac Mini OBS. Transparent overlays over your video, animated, branded, no third-party overlay service.

**Laptop can be completely off.** The Mac Mini handles everything. You close the laptop, lofi runs. You open the laptop, start OBS, press a Stream Deck button — you're live. Press it again when done — back to lofi. Close the laptop.

**No SSH. No PowerShell. No ritual.**

### What It Requires to Set Up

**Hardware needed:**
- Mac Mini M4 base model (16GB RAM) — **$499 new**
- Gigabit ethernet switch (if not already in apartment) — $15–20
- 2× Cat6 ethernet cables (Mac Mini + laptop to switch) — $10

**Software (all free):**
- OBS Studio v31.1+ — free, open source
- NDI Runtime v6.3+ — free, register at ndi.video
- DistroAV plugin (formerly OBS-NDI) v6.1.1+ — free, open source
- Install on **both** the Mac Mini and the Windows laptop

**One-time setup steps:**

| Step | Time |
|---|---|
| Install OBS + NDI Runtime + DistroAV on Mac Mini | 20 min |
| Install NDI Runtime + DistroAV on Windows laptop | 15 min |
| Configure Mac Mini OBS: Scene 1 (lofi media source) + Scene 2 (NDI input) | 30 min |
| Configure laptop OBS: enable NDI output of full canvas | 15 min |
| Set up YouTube Scheduled Stream (Auto-start ON, Auto-stop OFF) | 15 min |
| Configure Stream Deck scene switching (WebSocket to Mac Mini OBS) | 15 min |
| Wire both machines to gigabit switch via ethernet | 10 min |
| Test NDI connection, verify Mac Mini sees laptop as source | 30–60 min |
| First live test, verify YouTube stream health | 30 min |
| 24-hour burn-in test (passive) | 24 hrs |
| **Total active setup time** | **3–5 hours** |

> ⚠️ macOS 15 (Sequoia) has a known bug where OBS won't discover NDI sources even with permissions granted. Fix: launch OBS from Terminal once, grant Terminal "Local Network" permission. One-time setup annoyance, not an ongoing issue.

### YouTube Configuration (Critical)

In YouTube Studio → Manage → Schedule Stream:
- **Auto-start: ON** — stream begins the moment Mac Mini OBS connects
- **Auto-stop: OFF** — YouTube does NOT end the stream on brief encoder disconnects
- Encoder: H.264, CBR, 2-second keyframe interval, 4–8 Mbps
- Use Scheduled Stream **always** — never the "Go Live" button (90% of 24/7 failures trace to the Go Live button)

### Recurring Maintenance

- **Weekly:** Restart OBS on Mac Mini (prevents audio drift and memory buildup after 72h+). Takes 10 seconds. Auto-start reconnects to YouTube automatically.
- **Version pinning:** Disable auto-updates for OBS and NDI on Mac Mini after confirming everything works. An OBS update can break NDI compatibility overnight.
- **Never on macOS:** No forced OS restarts. Windows would be the #1 risk here — Mac eliminates it entirely.

### Ongoing Costs After Mac Mini Purchase

| Item | Cost |
|---|---|
| OBS Studio | Free |
| DistroAV (NDI plugin) | Free |
| NDI Runtime + Tools | Free |
| Restream Standard | ~$16/mo (already paying — no change) |
| Electricity (Mac Mini M4) | ~$22/year |
| DigitalOcean VPS (optional keepalive) | $6/mo |

> The VPS doesn't have to go away. It can stay as a fallback — if the Mac Mini ever has a problem, SSH in, restart FFmpeg, lofi is back while you troubleshoot.

### What Happens If Something Goes Wrong While Live

| Scenario | What Viewers See | What You Do |
|---|---|---|
| Your internet drops briefly | Buffering spinner, stream resumes | Nothing — Speedify + dual-WAN handles it |
| Your internet drops long enough for YouTube to end the event | Stream ends, becomes VOD | Restart the scheduled stream in YouTube Studio |
| Your laptop OBS crashes mid-stream | Mac Mini shows black or frozen on Scene 2 | Switch Stream Deck to Scene 1 (lofi) — or it auto-shows fallback image |
| Mac Mini OBS crashes | Stream ends entirely | Reopen OBS on Mac Mini — auto-reconnects to YouTube via Scheduled Stream |

